        <h3>Basic http server</h3>
      </div>
      <div class = "col s12">
        <p>NodeJS provides us with helpful modules out of the box. One of these is called http. Using http
        we can start up a server that will respond with a greeting.</p>
        <pre>
          <code>
<span style="color:purple;">var</span> http = require("http");

http.createServer(function(req, res){
  res.write("Hello there!");
  res.end();
}).listen(3000);
          </code>
        </pre>
      </div>


      <div class = "col s12" id = "httprequest">
        <h3>Basic http request</h3>
      </div>
      <div class = "aaa col s12">
        <p>We can use the http module to make requests for webpages.</p>
        <pre>
          <code>
var http = require("http");

http.request({
  host: "example.com",
  path: "/"
}, function(response){
  var webpage = "";
  response.on("data", function(data){
    webpage += data;
  });
  response.on("end", function(){
    console.log(webpage);
  });
}).end();
          </code>
        </pre>
      </div>

      <div class = "col s12" id = "httprequestimage">
        <h3>Basic image download using http request</h3>
      </div>
      <div class = "xxx col s12">
        <p>Let's use http.request to fetch an image and then we'll use another module named fs to save that image.</p>
        <pre>
          <code>
var http = require("http");
var fs = require("fs");

var writeStream = fs.createWriteStream("ourImage.jpg");

http.request({
  host: "i.imgur.com",
  path: "/gmRbksB.jpg"
}, function(response){
  response.on("data", function(data){
    writeStream.write(data);
  });
}).end();
          </code>
        </pre>
        <p>var writeStream is simply a file in which we can write data into chunks at a time. The correct term is a stream.</p>
